        "text": "15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For so is the will of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Better, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "for thus it is the will of God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This was to be the chief, if not the only, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "apologia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of Christians to the charges brought against them. They were accused of being evil-doers. They were to be conspicuous for well-doing. In the Greek for “put to silence” we have the word used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 22:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 22:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 1:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 4:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the primary meaning of which was “to enforce silence by a gag or muzzle.” The word “ignorance,” used elsewhere in the New Testament only in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 15:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", implies something more than a mere ignorance of facts. One might almost describe it as a settled incapacity for knowing and judging rightly. The “foolish men” are the accusers and slanderers of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 2:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather than the official authorities of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 2:13-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
