  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 15.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For so is the will of God, that with well-doing ye may put to silence the ignorance of foolish men.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The Gentiles speak against the Christians as evil-doers; they are to put their accusers to silence by well-doing; this is to be their answer rather than indignant self-vindication. The Greek word rendered \"put to silence\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "φιμοῦν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") means literally \"to muzzle\" (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 22:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 4:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 9:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The word for \"ignorance\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἀγνωσία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") occurs, besides this passage, only in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 15:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it evidently means \"culpable, self-caused ignorance.\" The word for \"foolish\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἄφρων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is a strong one - it means \"senseless\" (comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Corinthians 15:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Here it has the article, \"the foolish men,\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " those \"who speak against you as evil-doers.\" 1 Peter 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Put to silence (φιμοῦν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A very graphic word, meaning to muzzle or gag. Compare 1 Corinthians 9:9; 1 Timothy 5:18. See on Matthew 22:12.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "A very graphic word, meaning to muzzle or gag. Compare ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 9:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Timothy 5:18",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". See on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 22:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ignorance (ἀγνωσίαν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In classical Greek it is an ignorance arising from not coming into contact with the person or thing to be known. It occurs only once again in the New Testament, 1 Corinthians 15:34. Here it signifies not want of acquaintance, but of understanding; a state of ignorance.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "In classical Greek it is an ignorance arising from not coming into contact with the person or thing to be known. It occurs only once again in the New Testament, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Corinthians 15:34",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". Here it signifies not want of acquaintance, but of understanding; a state of ignorance.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of foolish men (τῶν ἀφρόνων ἀνθρώπων)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Of the foolish men; the article referring to those just mentioned, who speak against them as evil-doers. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
